<subSubSection pageId="59" pageNumber="60" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,1401,2041]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1473,1500]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Description.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[404,502,1474,1500]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">holotype</typeStatus>
NTM C3949 is 
<quantity box="[690,767,1473,1501]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" unit="cm" value="6.5">6.5 cm</quantity>
high and 
<quantity box="[881,937,1474,1501]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" unit="cm" value="6.0">6 cm</quantity>
wide, the stalk is 
<quantity box="[1145,1201,1474,1501]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" unit="cm" value="2.0">2 cm</quantity>
high (
<figureCitation box="[1275,1373,1474,1500]" captionStart="FIGURE 49" captionStartId="64.[151,250,1967,1992]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,273,1941]" captionTargetId="figure@64.[203,1385,273,1941]" captionTargetPageId="64" captionText="FIGURE 49. Litophyton type specimens: a, L. simplex n. sp., holotype NTM C3949; b, L. snakeensis n. sp., holotype NTM C10439; c, L. squamatum n. sp., holotype NTM C 4136. Scale at c 1 cm, a-b, natural size." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3765027" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3765027/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 49a</figureCitation>
). The polyps are up to 
<quantity box="[338,438,1510,1537]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" unit="mm" value="0.8">0.80 mm</quantity>
wide and 
<quantity box="[553,653,1509,1537]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" unit="mm" value="0.95">0.95 mm</quantity>
high, and grouped in long catkins.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,1401,2041]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,276,1546,1572]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Polyps</emphasis>
. Without clear arrangement of sclerites (
<figureCitation box="[716,811,1546,1573]" captionStart="FIGURE 42" captionStartId="55.[151,250,1910,1935]" captionTargetBox="[187,1390,185,1880]" captionTargetId="figure@55.[178,1409,181,1884]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="FIGURE 42. Lateral views polyp armature of Litophyton species: a, L. brewerensis n. sp., holotype NTM C4050; b, L. legiopolypum (Verseveldt &amp; Alderslade, 1982) holotype AMG 14806; c, L. oxleyensis n. sp., holotype NTM C4669; d, L. simplex n. sp., holotype NTM C3949; e, L. snakeensis n. sp., holotype NTM C10439; f, L. squamatum n. sp., holotype NTM C 4136; g-h, L. compactum (Verseveldt, 1966) holotype RMNH 2236 (after Verseveldt; magnification was not indicated by him)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3765013" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3765013/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 42d</figureCitation>
). Abaxial point sclerites are spindles, up to 
<quantity box="[1278,1375,1546,1573]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.40 mm</quantity>
long, with simple tubercles (
<figureCitation box="[400,495,1581,1608]" captionStart="FIGURE 50" captionStartId="65.[151,250,1910,1935]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,181,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@65.[190,1397,181,1884]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="FIGURE 50. Litophyton simplex n. sp., holotype NTM C3949; a, abaxial point spindles; b-c, lateral, adaxial point, tentacle, and polyp stalk sclerites; d, supporting bundle spindle, partly; e-f, sclerites of surface layer top of stalk; g-h, sclerites of surface layer base of stalk; i-j, spindles of interior base of stalk; k, tuberculation of interior base stalk spindle. Scale at a also applies to d, e, h, j; scale at i also applies to f; scale at b also applies to g." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3765029" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3765029/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 50a</figureCitation>
). Scales and rods, 
<quantity box="[698,852,1582,1609]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="12.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" unit="mm" value="0.075" valueMax="0.12" valueMin="0.03">0.03-0.12 mm</quantity>
long, are present laterally and adaxially, and they are also present in the tentacles and polyp stalk (
<figureCitation box="[634,713,1617,1644]" captionStart="FIGURE 50" captionStartId="65.[151,250,1910,1935]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,181,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@65.[190,1397,181,1884]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="FIGURE 50. Litophyton simplex n. sp., holotype NTM C3949; a, abaxial point spindles; b-c, lateral, adaxial point, tentacle, and polyp stalk sclerites; d, supporting bundle spindle, partly; e-f, sclerites of surface layer top of stalk; g-h, sclerites of surface layer base of stalk; i-j, spindles of interior base of stalk; k, tuberculation of interior base stalk spindle. Scale at a also applies to d, e, h, j; scale at i also applies to f; scale at b also applies to g." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3765029" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3765029/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
b-c). Supporting bundle without projecting spindles or one projecting for a maximum distance of 
<quantity box="[493,593,1654,1681]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" unit="mm" value="0.1">0.10 mm</quantity>
, composed of spindles, up to 1.00 mm long, with simple tubercles (
<figureCitation box="[1329,1424,1653,1680]" captionStart="FIGURE 51" captionStartId="66.[151,248,1910,1935]" captionTargetBox="[194,1393,184,1879]" captionTargetId="figure@66.[190,1397,181,1884]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="FIGURE 51. Litophyton nigrescens (Roxas, 1933), holotype SMF 61; a, lateral views polyp armature; b-c, abaxial point spindles; d, tentacle scales; e, lateral, adaxial, and polyp stalk scales; f, supporting bundle spindles, partly; g, sclerites of surface layer top of stalk; h, sclerites of surface layer base of stalk; i-j, spindles of interior base of stalk. Scale at h also applies to b-c, f-g, j; scale at d also applies to e." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3765031" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3765031/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 51d</figureCitation>
). Several polyp sclerites have an optically black inner core.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,1401,2041]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,460,1725,1752]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Surface layer top stalk</emphasis>
. Spindles and unilaterally spinose spindles, up to 
<quantity box="[998,1095,1725,1753]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.50 mm</quantity>
long, with simple and complex tubercles (
<figureCitation box="[264,343,1761,1788]" captionStart="FIGURE 50" captionStartId="65.[151,250,1910,1935]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,181,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@65.[190,1397,181,1884]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="FIGURE 50. Litophyton simplex n. sp., holotype NTM C3949; a, abaxial point spindles; b-c, lateral, adaxial point, tentacle, and polyp stalk sclerites; d, supporting bundle spindle, partly; e-f, sclerites of surface layer top of stalk; g-h, sclerites of surface layer base of stalk; i-j, spindles of interior base of stalk; k, tuberculation of interior base stalk spindle. Scale at a also applies to d, e, h, j; scale at i also applies to f; scale at b also applies to g." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3765029" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3765029/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
e-f).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,1401,2041]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,481,1797,1824]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Surface layer base stalk</emphasis>
. Capstans, derivatives of capstans, spindles and unilaterally spinose spindles, all with simple and complex tubercles (
<figureCitation box="[490,570,1833,1860]" captionStart="FIGURE 50" captionStartId="65.[151,250,1910,1935]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,181,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@65.[190,1397,181,1884]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="FIGURE 50. Litophyton simplex n. sp., holotype NTM C3949; a, abaxial point spindles; b-c, lateral, adaxial point, tentacle, and polyp stalk sclerites; d, supporting bundle spindle, partly; e-f, sclerites of surface layer top of stalk; g-h, sclerites of surface layer base of stalk; i-j, spindles of interior base of stalk; k, tuberculation of interior base stalk spindle. Scale at a also applies to d, e, h, j; scale at i also applies to f; scale at b also applies to g." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3765029" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3765029/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
g-h). The spindles are up to 
<quantity box="[873,970,1833,1861]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.50 mm</quantity>
long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,1401,2041]" box="[199,1380,1869,1897]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,354,1869,1896]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Interior stalk</emphasis>
. Spindles, up to 1.00 mm long, with simple tubercles (
<figureCitation box="[948,1043,1869,1896]" captionStart="FIGURE 50" captionStartId="65.[151,250,1910,1935]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,181,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@65.[190,1397,181,1884]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="FIGURE 50. Litophyton simplex n. sp., holotype NTM C3949; a, abaxial point spindles; b-c, lateral, adaxial point, tentacle, and polyp stalk sclerites; d, supporting bundle spindle, partly; e-f, sclerites of surface layer top of stalk; g-h, sclerites of surface layer base of stalk; i-j, spindles of interior base of stalk; k, tuberculation of interior base stalk spindle. Scale at a also applies to d, e, h, j; scale at i also applies to f; scale at b also applies to g." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3765029" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3765029/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 50k</figureCitation>
), and pointed ends (
<figureCitation box="[1261,1341,1869,1896]" captionStart="FIGURE 50" captionStartId="65.[151,250,1910,1935]" captionTargetBox="[190,1397,181,1884]" captionTargetId="figure@65.[190,1397,181,1884]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="FIGURE 50. Litophyton simplex n. sp., holotype NTM C3949; a, abaxial point spindles; b-c, lateral, adaxial point, tentacle, and polyp stalk sclerites; d, supporting bundle spindle, partly; e-f, sclerites of surface layer top of stalk; g-h, sclerites of surface layer base of stalk; i-j, spindles of interior base of stalk; k, tuberculation of interior base stalk spindle. Scale at a also applies to d, e, h, j; scale at i also applies to f; scale at b also applies to g." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3765029" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3765029/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 50</figureCitation>
i-j).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1357,1906,1933]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,1401,2041]" box="[199,1357,1906,1933]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,331,1906,1932]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Etymology.</emphasis>
The Latin 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Van" authorityYear="2020" box="[450,533,1906,1932]" class="Anthozoa" family="Nephtheidae" genus="Litophyton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis box="[450,533,1906,1932]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, simple, referring to the simple tuberculation of the sclerites of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,704,1941,1969]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,1401,2041]" box="[199,704,1941,1969]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,341,1941,1968]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Distribution</emphasis>
. Great Barrier Reef: Davies reef.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="59" pageNumber="60" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1437,1401,2041]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,313,1978,2004]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Remarks.</emphasis>
The species resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="(Roxas, 1933)" baseAuthorityName="Roxas" baseAuthorityYear="1933" box="[568,873,1978,2004]" class="Anthozoa" family="Nephtheidae" genus="Litophyton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="nigrescens">
<emphasis box="[568,713,1979,2004]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">L. nigrescens</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Roxas" box="[726,865,1978,2004]" firstAuthor="Roxas" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" pagination="345 - 470" refId="ref42531" refString="Roxas, H. A. (1933) Philippine Alcyonaria, II. The families Alcyoniidae and Nephthyidae. Philippine Journal of Science, 50 (4), 345 - 470." type="journal article" year="1933">Roxas, 1933</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
(
